"1388–1421":"1388–1421","1335–1362":"1335–1362","1345–1403":"1345–1403","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","12 May 1388":"12 May 1388","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1359":"1359","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","about 8 March 1361":"about 8 March 1361","28 August 1362":"28 August 1362","St Mary's Church, West Horsley, Surrey, England":"West Horsley, Surrey, England","Westminster Abbey, Westminster, London, England":"London, England","Berners Hall, West Horsley, Surrey, England":"West Horsley, Surrey, England","West Horsley, Surrey, England":"West Horsley, Surrey, England","Tower of London, London, England":"Tower of London, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berners","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Bernières (Calvados)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":20,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir James Berners was born about 8 March 1361, in West Horsley, Surrey, England, his father, Sir John de Berners, was 26 and his mother, Katherine St Omer, was 15. He married Anne Briwere Barew in 1380, in West Horsley, Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1388, in Tower of London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 27, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"about 8 March 1361–1388":"umbes 8. märts 1361–1388","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1361–1388":"1361–1388","1365–1402":"1365–1402","1388–1421":"1388–1421","1335–1362":"1335–1362","1345–1403":"1345–1403","1440":"1440","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","12 May 1388":"12. mai 1388","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1359":"1359","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","about 8 March 1361":"umbes 8. märts 1361","28 August 1362":"28. august 1